observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the following: 


a.	Petty Cash Custodian to regularly monitor the payment of the Petty Cash Fund and replenish it when disbursements therefrom reach at least 75% or as needed to ensure that the fund is sufficient to cover the petty operating expenses of the Municipality;

b. 	Petty Cash Custodian to record all the necessary information in the cashbook to facilitate immediate tracking and comparing of recorded transactions with the respective paid petty vouchers;


c. 	Municipal Accountant to observe the Pro-forma Accounting Entries provided in Section 52 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and

d. Officials/   Employees concerned to formulate internal guidelines/ policies on the use of Petty Cash Fund to ensure efficiency, economy, and effectiveness in the disbursement of government funds.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive and other municipal officials concerned agreed to do the following:

a.Submit the lacking supporting documents indicated in the attached schedule in order to establish the necessity, validity, propriety and legality of the disbursements made;

b.	Check the propriety and validity of the claims for meals, snacks and catering services and prospectively disallow the payment unless these are duly supported with proper and complete documentation in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-001; 

c.	Strictly adhere with the provisions of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in all its procurement activity. Alternative methods of procurement shall be resorted to only in highly exceptional cases provided for under R.A. No. 9184. In all instances, the procuring entity shall ensure that the most advantageous price for the Municipality is being obtained.

d.Henceforth, ensure that expenses incurred in entertaining visitors and guests should be charged against the RATA of the concerned municipal officials and department heads; and

e.	Discontinue the practice of serving meals and snacks during regular meetings or normal activities of the Municipality in order to observe economy and austerity measures in the use of government funds and refrain from incurring expenses that are considered irregular, unnecessary and excessive as per COA Circular No. 2012-003, to avoid suspension and disallowance in audit.

3.15 	We recommended and  the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following:
1.	Inventory Committee to prepare the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) to establish the reliability of the conduct of actual physical count of PPEs in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
2.	Inventory Committee to adhere to the RPCPPE reporting guidelines outlined in Section 57 of Volume II of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for LGUs;
3.	General Services Officer to update and prepare the property cards for each class of PPE, conduct periodic reconciliation with the records of the Accounting Office, and immediately effect necessary adjustments, if any; and
4.	Personnel concerned to consider the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006, and to reclassify the PPE accounts below the ₱50,000.00 threshold to its appropriate semi-expendable property account and adjust the beginning balance in the Statement of Changes in Net Assets/Equity in compliance with COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Strictly enforce the settlement of unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2018 and thereafter;
Stop granting additional cash advance to officers and employees unless the previous one has been fully liquidated to avoid accumulation of the same;
Initiate appropriate actions against erring officials and employees, if warranted;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to send written demand letter to officers/employees with accountability that is no longer connected with the municipality.
